EXECUTIVE SUMMARY


1    Midland Resources, Inc. (Midland) manufactures ferric chloride, ferrous chloride and other chemicals for the water treatment industry using chlorine gas as one of the raw materials.  Chlorine has been identified by the Environmental Protection Agency as a regulated substance subject to section 112 (r) of the Clean Air Act, which required the preparation of this Risk Management Plan (RMP).  Midland is subject to the OSHA process safety management standard and is submitting a program level 3 Risk Management Plan.

The facility is located at 10 Bremen Ave., St. Louis, MO in what is primarily an industrial district near downtown St. Louis and the Mississippi River.  

2    It is Midland's policy to adhere to all applicable federal and state rules and regulations.

The owners and management of this facility regard employee and public safety as a very serious matter and have taken many precautions to maintain a safe working and public environment.  Some of these steps include:

7 Installing chlorine sensors and alarms;
7 Installing an automatic shutoff valve on the railcar unloading system;
7 Instituting safe operating procedures;
7 Training employees in safety programs and procedures;
7 Writing a comprehensive Emergency Response Plan;
7 Coordinating with the Local Emergency Planning Committee (LEPC).


3    Process Description

Chlorine gas is received in 90-ton rail tank cars   Normally, only one rail tank car is present on-site at a time.  However, when the quantity in one car is low (approximately 10 tons), a second car is ordered.  They are stored under ambient temperatures which can exceed 100 degrees F in the summer.  Normal internal pressure is 60 to70 psi, but on a hot day pressures may reach 180 psi in the process. 

